content.problemStatement:
So far, we have learned how `for` loops control repetition by using a loop variable (e.g., `i`). The scope of this loop variable is limited to the loop itself, meaning it is only **accessible within the loop**. Once the loop ends, the variable goes out of scope and can no longer be accessed outside the loop.

This ensures that the loop variable does not interfere with other parts of the program, preventing conflicts and improving code organization.

---

**Example:**
```c
#include

int main() {
    // Example 1: When Loop variable declared inside the loop
    for (int i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
        // 'i' is only accessible within the loop
        printf("%d\n", i);
    }
    // 'i' is no longer accessible here because it was declared inside the loop
    // Uncommenting the following line will cause an error:
    // printf("i is: %d", i);

    // Example 2: When Loop variable declared outside the loop
    int j;  // Declared outside the loop, so it remains accessible after the loop

    // Loop from 11 to 13
    for (j = 11; j <= 13; j++) {
        printf("%d\n", j);  // Print the current value of j
    }

    // Since 'j' was declared outside the loop, it can still be accessed here
    printf("Final value of j: %d\n", j);  // 'j' is still accessible after the loop

    return 0;
}
```
**Expected output:**
```default
1
2
3
11
12
13
Final value of j: 14
```

